    <item>
      <title>Immutability Changes Evrything</title>
      <link>https://jeqo.github.io/notes/immutability-changes-everything/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 16 Jan 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://jeqo.github.io/notes/immutability-changes-everything/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Immutability is one of those concepts that could appear simple
and even dumb at first (&amp;ldquo;yeah, a thing that never changes&amp;rdquo;)
but it is incredible useful and fundamental for distributed systems:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We &lt;strong&gt;need immutability&lt;/strong&gt; to coordinate at a distance&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is pretty much related with Pat&amp;rsquo;s previous paper:
&lt;a href=&#34;../data-on-the-outside-vs-data-on-the-inside/&#34;&gt;Data on the Outside vs Data on the Inside&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;[&amp;hellip;] and we &lt;strong&gt;can afford immutability&lt;/strong&gt;, as storage gets cheaper.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
